Part 1 - use ARIMA(p,d,q) model to forecast beer sales for all months of 1990 using the following two multi-step forecasting approaches. For each model, check mean, autocorrelation and normality of the residuals. Confirm if the residuals are white noise.

Mean Residuals: The computed mean of the residuals was -0.01226384, indicating a very slight negative bias but close enough to zero for practical purposes. ACF of Residuals: The ACF plot did not show significant correlations, suggesting that the residuals might be white noise, although further statistical testing would be needed for confirmation. Normality Test: The Shapiro-Wilk test returned a p-value of 5.15e-07, indicating that the residuals do not follow a normal distribution. This suggests potential issues with the model assumptions or that transformation might be needed. The non normality suggests that residuals are not fully white noise

# Calculate metrics for each model
results <- map_df(model_listbeer, function(model) {
  residuals <- residuals(model)
  acf_res <- Box.test(residuals, type="Ljung-Box")
  shapiro_res <- shapiro.test(residuals)
  tibble(
    mean = mean(residuals),
    p_value_acf = acf_res$p.value,
    p_value_normality = shapiro_res$p.value
  )
})

# Add model identifier

# Plotting

  gather(key = "Statistic", value = "Value", -model) %>%

Part B: our task is to adopt an algorithm to create a time series that contains a seat price for each month starting from January 2001 to December 2013. You need to do this for the 3 classes of seats. Note that all 3 seat classes have sale prices for January 2001 so you should not have any start up issues. Please clearly explain why you adopted your algorithm and what other alternatives you may have considered and why you rejected the alternatives.

I used three interpolation methods to fill in missing data ans ensure a seamless time series- 1.Linear interpolation is a straightforward technique that uses a straight line to connect two points and fills in any gaps by using the linear relationship between them. When data evolves gradually and reliably, its fast and efficient. 2.Polynomial interpolation: This technique fits a wide range of curves and is well-suited to more intricate and unstable data patterns since it makes use of polynomial functions. 3.Spline Interpolation: This technique combines the best features of the two earlier approaches to produce a flexible, smooth curve that closely fits the data points by using segments of polynomials. This approach works very well with data that fluctuates frequently and unexpectedly.

Based on our analysis, spline interpolation was selected. It proved to be the most effective at smoothing out rapid fluctuations and providing a realistic, continuous data flow. Spline interpolation excelled in capturing the markets volatility smoothly, ensuring month-to-month transitions were both realistic and reflective of true market dynamics. This method maintained critical market details better than the simpler linear interpolation, which often oversimplified trends. Linear Interpolation: Rejected due to its oversimplification, which could miss non-linear market trends. Polynomial Interpolation: Not chosen because it could exaggerate market movements, creating unrealistic peaks and troughs.

# Function to load, preprocess, interpolate, and plot data
process_and_plot_data <- function(file_path, title_suffix) {
  # Load and preprocess data
  data <- read.csv(file_path)
  data$DateOfSale <- as.Date(data$DateOfSale, format = "%m/%d/%Y")
  data$Year <- year(data$DateOfSale)
  data$Month <- month(data$DateOfSale)

  # Aggregate data by month
  monthly_data <- data %>%
    group_by(Year, Month) %>%
    summarize(price = mean(price), .groups = 'drop')

  # Generate complete time series data frame
  complete_range <- expand.grid(Year = 2001:2013, Month = 1:12)
  complete_range$Date <- as.Date(with(complete_range, paste(Year, Month, "1", sep="-")))

  # Merge and interpolate
  full_data <- merge(complete_range, monthly_data, by = c("Year", "Month"), all = TRUE)
  full_data$spline_price <- na.spline(full_data$price)
  full_data$poly_price <- na.approx(full_data$price, method = "constant", f = 0, ties = mean)
  full_data$linear_price <- na.approx(full_data$price)

  # Plotting function for comparing methods
  ggplot(full_data, aes(x = Date)) +
    geom_point(aes(y = price), color = "grey", size = 2, alpha = 0.5) +  # Original data in grey
    geom_line(aes(y = spline_price, color = "Spline Interpolation"), size = 1) +
    geom_line(aes(y = poly_price, color = "Polynomial Interpolation"), size = 1) +
    geom_line(aes(y = linear_price, color = "Linear Interpolation"), size = 1) +
    scale_color_manual(values = c("Spline Interpolation" = "red", "Polynomial Interpolation" = "blue", "Linear Interpolation" = "green")) +
    labs(title = paste("Comparison of Interpolation Methods for", title_suffix, "Seats"),
         x = "Date", y = "Price",
         caption = "Grey points represent original data. Lines show interpolated data using different methods.") +
    theme_minimal() +
    scale_x_date(date_breaks = "2 years", date_labels = "%Y") +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1), legend.position = "bottom")
}

#We will try to compare interpolation for first five years for more understanding Smoothness: The smooth curve produced by spline interpolation looks to follow the datas general trend rather than conforming too closely to isolated variations. By doing so, one can better grasp underlying trends without becoming unduly affected by small price fluctuations or anomalies. Response: The spline curve is sufficiently sensitive to catch notable changes in the data, such as the peak around 2004. However, it does not have the abruptness or oversimplicity of linear interpolation that might occasionally result from polynomial interpolation. Balance: Spline offers an excellent trade-off between preventing overfitting, which is a potential hazard with high-degree polynomial interpolation, and preserving a close match to the data.

library(tidyverse)
library(zoo)

# Function to process, interpolate, and plot data for a specific dataset and time period
process_and_plot_data <- function(file_path, title_suffix) {
  # Load data
  data <- read.csv(file_path)
  data$DateOfSale <- as.Date(data$DateOfSale, format = "%m/%d/%Y")
  data <- filter(data, DateOfSale >= as.Date("2001-01-01") & DateOfSale <= as.Date("2005-12-31"))
  data$Year <- year(data$DateOfSale)
  data$Month <- month(data$DateOfSale)

  # Aggregate data by month
  monthly_data <- data %>%
    group_by(Year, Month) %>%
    summarize(price = mean(price), .groups = 'drop')

  # Generate complete time series data frame for the period 2001-2005
  complete_range <- expand.grid(Year = 2001:2005, Month = 1:12)
  complete_range$Date <- as.Date(with(complete_range, paste(Year, Month, "1", sep="-")))

  # Merge and interpolate
  full_data <- merge(complete_range, monthly_data, by = c("Year", "Month"), all = TRUE)
  full_data$spline_price <- na.spline(full_data$price, na.rm = FALSE)
  full_data$poly_price <- na.approx(full_data$price, method = "constant", f = 0, na.rm = FALSE)
  full_data$linear_price <- na.approx(full_data$price, na.rm = FALSE)

  # Plotting function for comparing methods
  ggplot(full_data, aes(x = Date)) +
    geom_point(aes(y = price), color = "grey", size = 2, alpha = 0.5) +  # Original data in grey
    geom_line(aes(y = spline_price, color = "Spline Interpolation"), size = 1) +
    geom_line(aes(y = poly_price, color = "Polynomial Interpolation"), size = 1) +
    geom_line(aes(y = linear_price, color = "Linear Interpolation"), size = 1) +
    scale_color_manual(values = c("Spline Interpolation" = "red", "Polynomial Interpolation" = "blue", "Linear Interpolation" = "green")) +
    labs(title = paste("Comparison of Interpolation Methods for", title_suffix, "Seats (2001-2005)"),
         x = "Date", y = "Price",
         caption = "Grey points represent original data. Lines show interpolated data using different methods.") +
    theme_minimal() +
    scale_x_date(date_breaks = "1 year", date_labels = "%Y") +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1), legend.position = "bottom")
}

library(tidyverse)

library(lubridate)

# Define a function to load data, process, and plot
process_and_plot_data <- function(file_path, title_suffix) {
  # Load data
  data <- read.csv(file_path)
  data$DateOfSale <- as.Date(data$DateOfSale, format = "%m/%d/%Y")
  data <- data %>%
    mutate(Year = year(DateOfSale), Month = month(DateOfSale)) %>%
    select(-DateOfSale)

  # Aggregate data by month
  monthly_data <- data %>%
    group_by(Year, Month) %>%
    summarise(price = mean(price), .groups = 'drop')

  # Generate complete time series data frame from Jan 2001 to Dec 2013
  complete_range <- expand.grid(Year = 2001:2013, Month = 1:12)
  complete_range$Date <- as.Date(with(complete_range, paste(Year, Month, "1", sep="-")))

  # Merge and interpolate
  full_data <- merge(complete_range, monthly_data, by = c("Year", "Month"), all.x = TRUE)
  full_data$interpolated_price <- na.spline(full_data$price, na.rm = FALSE)

  # Identify original and interpolated data points
  full_data$Type <- ifelse(is.na(full_data$price), "Interpolated", "Original")

  # Plotting
  ggplot(full_data, aes(x = Date, y = interpolated_price, group = 1)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = Type), size = 2, alpha = 0.5) +
    geom_line() +
    scale_color_manual(values = c("Original" = "black", "Interpolated" = "red")) +
    labs(title = paste("Interpolation Comparison for", title_suffix, "Seats (2001-2013)"),
         x = "Date", y = "Price",
         caption = "Black points represent original data; red points show interpolated data.") +
    theme_minimal() +
    scale_x_date(date_breaks = "1 year", date_labels = "%Y") +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1), legend.position = "bottom")
}
